@delivermypain  What do you say to the fact that Faker has been the most acclaimed pro player by other pro players and coaches throughout LOL history. You're in total disagreement with all the pros & coaches who have spent thousands of hours practicing and studying the game. Plenty of arrogant highly skilled pro players have had no problems acknowledging faker's exceptional talent. In his prime, pro players have tried pretty hard to convince people that faker's talents are really above the cut. Calling faker a god actually originated  It's a very common and agreed upon experience to not be able to notice what makes higher elo players better. If you ask any high elo player, 99% chance they'll say they didn't notice LCS players were better than them when they started playing, but realized as they got better. It's something I observed in going from unranked to diamond. Why do you think you're immune to this phenomena?   It's hard to judge skill in LOL. The micro game is actually very sensitive. By playing for a really long time you build intuitions about how to move relative to your opponent and tend to maintain a certain healthy distance. Bronze players haven't played long enough to do this naturally, and as a result they tend to take harass very often and get easily exploited by players of higher elo. When the high elo player sees that the healthy distance is broken, he feels something in his gut and either moves back or attacks in response to it. When two equally high elo players play against eachother, both will just maintain healthy distance and trade evenly and it won't seem that either of them are very skilled. But if you throw a bronze player in their, the bronze player will keep breaking healthy distance and the high elo player will harass on time. The high elo player will push him out quickly and the skill difference will be easily noticed.   In a macro sense, the games much more complicated than just "dancing around in the lane". What fights you can take is often decided by where the minions are in the side lines, what sorts of minion pushes are coming next, and specific level and item timings. That's usually the reason players don't fight when you think they should fight.  Heres some analysis on the micro game of apdo from an experienced coach who's dealt with some of the best players in the world ( last shadow ) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZblvfOK9ajI  Micro stuff is mostly intuitive ( you're not consciously making decisions, but working off gut responses built from practice ) Macro decisions on the other hand are usually conscious. Heres a game analysis by Montecristo to give you an impression of the complexity  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eztmFLkzAPg  What do you say to Fakers and other LCS pro's abilities to reach higher levels of challenger anytime they want? Sure if you reach challenger once, it's evidence that you're in the top .0001% ( top 1000 of 30 mil ). But if you can do it multiples times on alts casually, then doesn't that make it extremely likely that you're significantly above other players?  If professional players are so overrated, why is the professional scene so stable? When two parties are equally skilled, they go 50/50. If LCS players were overrated and not actual superior to the average masters / low challenger player, then new challenger teams would do better more frequently when they enter LCS. In reality, new challenger teams almost always fail when they move up to LCS. Usually specific high talent individuals have to be taken from challenger teams and trained to match LCS talent.  Why would pro teams waste so much time and money making pro players practice for 12 hrs a day if they're only just as good as some random low challenger slob who doesn't play as much?  Why do you think faker practicing diligently for 16 hours a day for years wouldn't put him a cut above the average challenger?  You're totally misguided and wrong to underestimate pro players based on some troll performances on alts in diamond games that mean nothing. Your opinions on pro games are horrible in a similar way to that bronze player who has no clue what's happening when they watch pro games.

Disagree 100%. These people are playing games in a public setting. Look at any sport and there are very clear divisions between people playing with the expectation to win, and people playing for fun. Entire leagues dedicated to making a profession out of their chosen game.   You do not however see professional athletes, or people who aspire to go professional, walk onto a baseball field in a public park, during a recreational league and then flip out when people aren't playing at the highest levels possible.   The same applies for league. Yes, there is a structure there for progression (just like in a recreational league in other sports) but it's still an unofficial public setting. More than that though, the matchmaking system is one specifically designed to try and give you a 50/50 win ratio, so it's inherently a system that's not designed for competitive play.   If you really want to take the game excessively serious then get a proper 5 man team and play together there, play in tournaments, or try to go pro. Going into solo q with the expectation of a super serious mature game is utter idiocy.

Dude, I've been playing for nearly a year now, placed s5 by the end of last season, b3 this season, climbed to b1 in two days and got bored so I stopped playing ranked, but I want to pick it up again.  Now, cs is one of my biggest issues. Since I've started following a couple streamers I've been working on it, and on my mistakes. I've been starting to actually SEE where I have to go, how I need to move, what objectives to take at what time, when to fight and when to disengage, of course most of it is probably still wrong, but I've been watching my games from a different point of view.  But that also makes me even more tilted, because when you're clueless you don't  mind your mistakes and everyone elses' (because you don't notice them), but there's certain games like today where I was playing Karma mid, and everyone who walked past my lane casually started farming my cs, exactly when I'm trying to actually focus on it rather than trading, killing, roaming, that's when I lose my temper. Botlane roams up chasing a kill, they get the kill, Vayne farms in my lane. Kha'Zix tries to gank but he's seen before he even leaves the bush, instead of turning around and leaving he crosses my lane and farms. Vayne roams up again and farms again. They didn't even push to the tower. And when I try to say something they tell me it's not actually MY cs, and that I need to stop crying. THAT is people who don't get how important cs is. Then again, at 10 minutes Vayne had 42 cs... And that's just one episode, I was playing Shen top a couple days ago and my whole team kept chasing kills and getting rekt, I couldn't say anything that I got laughed at. A totally winnable game was tragically lost.  How am I expected to climb like this?
